During an emergency call, the professor confessed to shooting his girlfriend
While calling the emergency line in a trembling voice, Professor Shannon Lamb admitted to the police that he had shot his girlfriend and that they needed to come to their home.
Lamb resolved that his "sweet dog" was alive and probably upset, and that the dead woman's family contacts could be found on her phone.
Inside, police found Amy Prentiss's body and a handwritten note on white office paper: "I'm so sorry and wish I could get it back, I loved Amy and she's the only one who ever loved me," the letter, which authorities say was signed by Lamb, read.
There was no suspicion that Lamb, who taught two online courses at Delta State University in Cleveland, Mississippi, would drive 300 miles to a school campus where police believe he shot and killed popular professor Ethan Schmidt in the doorway of his office.
Delta State University Police Chief Lynn Buford said university employees heard the shooting at 10:18 a.m.
Lamb is said to have made a fateful call to the emergency line shortly thereafter.
Finally came yet another death; Lamb took his own life when the police came for him.
The day after the school shooting forced students and faculty to hide behind locked doors, authorized authorities are still trying to figure out Lamb's motivation.
The details released by state investigators as well as students and staff who knew him combined to create an image of a talented but likely troubled teacher.
Students confirmed that they were looking forward to his lessons.
Police in Gautier, where Prentiss died, confirmed he had no criminal record or violent past.
Schmidt himself included Lamb in the book he wrote, thanking the "great people" with whom he shared his academic life.
Both taught at the Faculty of Social Sciences and History along with 17 other faculty members, and many students took classes with both at the same time.
At the same time, there were inclinations in terms of problems.
A student who praised Lamb, Brandon Beavers, said he also seemed agitated and shaky, "as if something was wrong with him."
Another student, Mikel Sykes, said Lamb told him he was dealing with stress at the end of the 2014-15 academic year.
Lamb had previously asked Delta State University for medical leave, saying he had a problem.
And this year he taught only two online courses.
Recent changes to the university's recruitment meant that the doctorate that Lamb had worked would not guarantee him an automatic term to become an assistant professor.
University President William LaForge said he was not aware of any conflict between Lamb and Schmidt, but that "Mr. Lamb seemed to be bothered by something."
Lamb will not answer these questions.
After he left campus, police caught his trail as he crossed the Arkansas state border back to Misissippi.
Before he could be arrested, Lamb killed himself with a single shot from a pistol in the yard of a house about a mile from his parents in suburban Greenville, Mississippi, Washington State Coroner Methel Johnson confirmed.
He left the car started on the street.
It wasn't immediately clear why Lamb had gone to the house, though Johnson said he probably knew people who lived there.
Lamb grew up in this county.
Lamb began working at the university, which has 3500 students in a city of about 12000 inhabitants, in 2009 and taught geography and education classes.
In the spring, he received his doctorate in education.
One of Lamb's longtime friends described him as smart, charismatic and funny.
Carla Hairston said she was 15 and Lamb was 20 when they met through mutual friends.
She was in high school with her friends, and he was the great older guy who taught her guitar for a few years.
He was quite a heartbreaker at the time.
The hearts of all the girls sparkled as soon as he appeared," said Hairston, now 40 and living in the Jackson suburb.
Lamb and Prentiss reportedly dated for some time.
During the emergency call, Lamb said, "I killed my wife," but the marriage record never existed.
They had a dog named Lightning who lived with them in a brick house adjacent to a branch of the River Gautier.
Police said the dog was fine.
Prentiss' ex-husband, Shawn O'Steen, said they split 15 years ago but remained friends and had a daughter, who is now 19.
"She was completely collapsed," O'Steen said of his daughter.
She was best friends with her mother.
O'Steen said he had not met Lamb, but he knew through his daughter Abigail that Lamb was interested in music and played blues.
Lamb met Prentiss when he and Abigail performed at a summer festival three years ago.
Later, they played random gigs together.
O'Steen said his daughter writes and sings her own music.
Prentiss was a nurse who worked for various online companies.
Mike Shaffer, bartender and occasional entertainment coordinator at The Julep Room, a dimly lit bar near Gautier, said he last saw Lamb and Prentiss on the night of September 5, after Lamb finished playing guitar and harmonica to a small crowd.
There was no sign of anything wrong.
"They were just a happy couple," he said.
We bantered and recorded each other's jokes.
I mean, they both had a good sense of humor.
Schmidt, the slain professor, led the seminar in his first year and specialized in indigenous American and colonial history, said Don Allan Mitchell, an English professor at the school.
He was married and had three young children.
He attended Emporia State University in Kansas and was president of the Boys' Student Club and Student Government.
At the Delta State campus in Cleveland on Tuesday night, about 900 people, including faculty members, staff, students, and community members, attended a candlelight commemoration.
Schmidt's wife, Liz, and brother Jeff Schnidt also attended a vigil during which the university choir sang "Bright Morning Star" and "Amazing Grace."
School resumed on Wednesday.
"We're trying to get our students to come back," LaForge said.
The crisis is over.
This is a day of healing.
Amy and Rogelio Solis filed a report in Cleveland, Mississippi.
Associated Press writers Emily Wagster Pettus in Greenville, Mississippi, and Rebecca Santana in New Orleans also contributed to the report.
This story has been edited to reflect the fact that police now claim that Lamb made an emergency call after killing Schmidt, and that although Lamb called Prentiss his wife, there is no evidence that they were actually married.
Toys R Us plans to hire fewer seasonal workers
Toys R Us says it won't hire as many seasonal workers as it did last year, but the maker of children's toys and products says it will give current and seasonal workers a chance to work more hours.
The company also said it plans to hire about 40,000 employees to work in stores and distribution centers across the country, down from 45,000 last season.
Most jobs will be part-time.
The company says it will begin recruiting candidates this month and will hire employees through October through December.
While the holidays themselves are months away, the shopping holiday season is approaching and companies are preparing to temporarily hire employees to help out in stores and sales, for shipping and delivering goods.
