UN chief says there is no military solution in Syria
Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon says his response to Russia's expedited military support for Syria is that "there is no military solution" to the conflict for nearly five years of conflict and more weapons will only exacerbate the violence and suffering of millions of people.
The UN chief again urged all parties, including the divided UN Security Council, to unite and support inclusive negotiations to find a political solution.
Ban told a news conference on Wednesday that he plans to meet with the foreign ministers of the five permanent councils of the countries — the US, Russia, China, Britain and France — on the sidelines of a ministerial session of the General Assembly later this month to discuss the situation in Syria.
He regretted that divisions in the Council and between the Syrian people and regional powers "have made this situation unsolvable."
Ban called on the five permanent members to show the solidarity and unity they have shown in reaching an Iran nuclear deal in resolving the crisis in Syria.
8 election numbers that show that Donald Trump in a real light
Some have tried to label him as a person who often changes his mind.
The others dismissed it as a failed joke.
And some are preparing for implosion.
But whether some Republicans try to drag Donald Trump down from the top of the election, they have failed (so far).
10 of the last 11 national polls show Donald Trump leading by double digits, and some are beginning to seriously question what that means for the real estate mogul's nomination chances.
Of course, this is only the beginning of the election cycle.
None of this is to say that Trump is likely to win the Republican nomination.
Experts point out that at this time in 2011, Rick Perry's leadership paved the way for Herman Cain's rise, and in the end, neither of them won a single position in the nomination process.
There are many reasons why he might run into a general election.
But outside groups like Jeb Bush's Super PAC and the conservative economic group Club for Growth realize Trump's will to endure and are beginning to dump their dollars in order to topple him.
Here are some recent poll numbers that suggest the real estate mogul isn't just a passing phase:
Trump's approval rating has turned 180 degrees.
Just before Donald Trump announced his candidacy in mid-June, a Monmouth University poll showed that only two in 10 Republicans had a positive view of the real estate mogul.
By mid-July, it was 40 percent.
At the beginning of August, it was 52 percent.
Now, six out of 10 Republicans have a favorable view of Donald Trump.
Roughly three in 10 say they have a negative opinion of him.
And these numbers hold up in the early stages.
After last week's Quinnipiac University poll, it was found that 60 percent of Republicans had a positive opinion of Trump.
Two-thirds of GOP voters would be happy with Trump as a candidate.
In a CNN/ORC poll conducted last week, 67 percent of Republicans said they would be either "excited" or "happy" with Trump as a candidate.
Only two in 10 said they would be "outraged" by his candidacy.
Only Ben Carson generates roughly the same level of enthusiasm as Trump (43 percent said they would be "excited" versus 40 percent who say the same about Trump).
Next closest in the level of enthusiasm?
Marco Rubio with only 21 percent.
On the other hand, 47 percent of Republican voters say they would be "dissatisfied" or "upset" if the company's favorite, Jeb Bush, became the nominee.
Most Republicans don't see Trump's temperament as a problem.
While Donald Trump has been widely criticized for his bombast and insults, 52 percent of Republican voters nationwide are in favor of the idea that the real estate mogul has the right temperament for the presidency, according to an ABC News/Washington Post poll Monday.
That number holds in the Iowa Senatorial Caucus, which is the first in the entire state where 52 percent of Republicans think he has the personality of a commander, according to Quinnipiac last week.
Still, 44 percent think he doesn't have the personality to serve effectively, and nearly 6 in 10 independents say his temperament doesn't belong in the White House, according to the ABC/Post.
Republican voters are getting used to the idea.
When they put on their scholarly hats, Republican voters think Trump is a real candidate.
When asked who is most likely to win the GOP nomination, four out of 10 said Trump would be the best choice, according to a CNN/ORC poll last week.
That's a change from late July, when four out of 10 were betting their money on Jeb Bush.
Full disclosure: GOP voters have not had the brightest crystal ball in the past.
At this time in the last cycle, 4 out of 10 Republicans chose Rick Perry as the winner of the candidacy against 28 percent for the eventual nomination of Mitt Romney.
Still, it turns out that a certain number of GOP voters see Trump's campaign as credible.
Even though Republicans have rallied around another candidate, Trump still beats almost everyone.
Some pundits point out that the fragmented field likely contributes to Trump's leadership, while anti-Trump support is diffusely spread among more than a dozen other candidates.
But a Monmouth University poll in early September shows that in a hypothetical head-to-head contest between Trump and most other Republican candidates, Trump almost always wins majority support.
He leads Carly Fiorina by 13 points, Marc Rubio by 14 points, Walker by 15 points, Jeb Bush by 19 points and Rand Paul, John Kasich, Chris Christie by 33 points each.
He's in a dead race with Ted Cruz.
The only candidate who beats him?
Ben Carson would have a wide 19-point lead over the trader in a hypothetical one-on-one match.
A bare majority of Donald Trump's supporters say they have already made up their minds.
A new CBS/NYT poll Tuesday shows that only more than half of voters who support Trump say they won't change their minds.
Obviously, a lot of things can change that, and no one can really say that they would never change their mind.
46 percent say they keep the back door open for change between candidates.
Still, Trump's current strongest opponent is his outsider colleague, neurosurgeon Ben Carson, but voters who consider their opinion final would be twice as likely to vote for Trump.
6 in 10 Republicans reportedly agree with Trump on the immigration issue.
Even since Donald Trump called immigrants from Mexico "rapists" in his campaign announcement speech, immigration has remained the main and central topic of conversation for 2016.
Some fear that Trump's bombast will lure key Hispanic voters away from the Republican Party and damage rebranding efforts.
But according to a new ABC/Post poll on Monday, six in 10 Republicans say they agree with Trump on immigration.
It seems that as long as the topic of immigration remains in the spotlight, Donald Trump will also stay.
Frustration with government is reaching new highs.
Donald Trump and Ben Carson now receive about half of the support from Republican voters, largely because of their outlying status.
Six out of 10 Republicans in Monday's new ABC/Post poll say they want a political outsider rather than someone with government experience.
And they are also very angry with Washington.
A Des Moines Register/Bloomberg poll in Iowa a few weeks ago revealed that three out of four Republicans in Iowa are frustrated with congressional Republicans, 54 percent are "dissatisfied" and 21 percent are "hellishly angry."
The House supported a larger share of the state's share of coal charges.
The Czech Republic will receive more than 400 million.
In the first reading, the Chamber of Deputies supported the government's amendment to the Mining Act, which regulates the amount of yield from fees from open-cast brown coal mining from mining companies.
Minister Jan Mládek (ČSSD) promised MPs that thanks to this, both the state treasury and municipal budgets would receive extra money.
The bill was criticized by opposition MPs, who fear that mining companies will no longer want to sponsor municipalities as they do now, because they will pay higher fees directly to the state budget. In the first reading, the Chamber of Deputies supported the government's amendment to the Mining Act, which means, among other things, that the state should receive a larger part of the revenue from fees from open-cast brown coal mining from mining companies.
The share of the state will increase to 67 percent, while the share of municipalities will decrease from the current 75 percent to 33 percent.
The draft also changes the method of calculating remuneration for minerals extracted by companies.
The change in fees for mineral extraction should bring CZK 427 million more to the state treasury than in 2013.
According to the government, it should have a neutral impact on municipal budget revenues because the fee should be higher.
Last year, municipalities received about CZK 450 million from fees and the state budget CZK 150 million.
From brown coal mining, about 200 million crowns went to municipalities and 66 million crowns to the state.
The amendment also envisages an increase in the payment for mining areas with permitted mining to CZK 1,000 per hectare per year.
The income from these payments is to continue to belong entirely to the municipalities.
Industry Minister Jan Mládek (ČSSD) told MPs that municipalities will receive CZK 14 million to 100 million annually instead of 14 million.
The amount of mining royalties will no longer be determined by law, but will be set by government regulation.
The remuneration is newly calculated as the product of the quantity of the extracted mineral and the rate for individual types of minerals.
According to the government, the reason for the change is, among other things, the possibility of a flexible response to the current economic situation.
ODS MP Marek Benda, however, warned that setting the fee by government decree may not be in accordance with the constitution.
According to Minister Mládek, however, this is not a tax because the state charges for a mineral that is state property.
Fees are paid only to municipalities whose territories are affected by mining.
In the case of underground coal mining, three-quarters of the money will go to municipalities and a quarter to the state.
The same ratio will be in the case of the extraction of radioactive rocks.
Part of the money collected by the state in mining royalties will be earmarked.
For example, 28 percent will have to go to repair damage after mining or to provide mining rescue services.
The bill was criticized by opposition MPs, who claimed in particular that it would harm municipalities affected by mining and regions.
For example, Michal Kučera (TOP 09 and Mayors) warned that mining companies will no longer want to sponsor municipalities as they have done so far, because they will pay higher fees directly to the state budget.
"It is not possible to tunnel one of the poorest regions just to have the finance minister improve his budget," said David Kádner (Úsvit), elected in the Ústí region.
Communist Party MP Hana Aulicka warned against the rise in unemployment in the Most region.
Kádner and Aulická unsuccessfully proposed to reject the amendment, Kučera wanted to return the law to the government for completion.
The explanatory memorandum states that, according to mining companies, the increase in fees will not be reflected in coal prices, because more than 90 percent of the prices are long-term contracted.
Major consumers, such as power stations or CHP plants, should therefore not feel the rise in prices.
"On the other hand, however, this fact increases the risk that mining organizations will compensate for the increase in reimbursements by trying to reduce their operating expenses, which would primarily mean a reduction in the number of employees," the government admits.
In its view, however, the increase in charges is acceptable from the point of view of employment.
According to Milan Urban (ČSSD), the rapporteur on the amendment, it is crucial that deputies know the conclusions regarding the updated energy concept and, in particular, the government's decision on coal mining limits, before approving the law.
If coal is mined beyond the limits, then it will have an impact on revenues for the state and municipalities, he stressed.
Urban disagrees with Mládek that the decision to break the limit at the Czechoslovak Army mine should be made only after 2020.
According to him, the limits at the ČSA mine should be broken for social, economic and long-term stability of the domestic energy sector.
