Jeremy Corbyn to debut on Prime Minister's Questions
Since his election, Mr Corbyn's PMQ debut has been eagerly awaited
New head Jeremy Corbyn will make his Prime Minister's Questions debut at a later date, and will be working with David Cameron for the first time.
Mr Corbyn will ask the first of his six assigned questions shortly after midday, while his performance is likely to be scrutinised by the media and MPs.
In a week-long statement, he called for "less theater and more facts."
He also stated that he could skip a few sessions he would leave for his colleagues.
The meeting will be the first parliamentary test of Mr Corby's leadership, following his appointment to the shadow cabinet and his speech at the annual TUC congress on Tuesday.
Meanwhile, the Labour leader's decision to stand quietly while singing the national anthem on duty on Tuesday marking the 75th anniversary of the Battle of Britain has been met with criticism from a number of Conservative MPs and is the focus of several front-page stories.
Mr Corbyn's decision not to sing the national anthem has attracted attention
Mr Corbyn's spokesman said he would "stand in respectful silence" and recognise "the heroism of the Royal Air Force in the Battle of Britain".
But Mr Corbyn's shadow cabinet member, Owen Smith, told BBC Two's Newsnight that he would advise the Labour leader to sing the national anthem "regardless" his belief that the monarchy should be abolished.
Nearly a dozen shadow ministers refused to serve on Mr Corbyn's top team, citing differences in the economy, defence and foreign affairs, and less than a sixth of parliamentary parties initially supported him as leader.
BBC political correspondent Robin Brant says political differences in work are also "piling up" after Mr Corbyn's appointment despite his position in the European Union and the government's benefit limit.
Mr. Corbyl told the TUC conference that the Workers' Party had put forward amended proposals to remove the whole idea of a benefit cap.
A few hours later, Mr Smith, secretary of shadow labour and pensions, said the party had "very clearly" opposed the government's plans to lower the cap from £26,000 to £23,000.
Mr Corbyn will be the fifth Workers' Party leader David Cameron has faced in the decade since his election as Conservative leader.
The Workers' Party leader, who has promised a different approach to politics, says he has ideas "from the crowd" for questions for Mr Cameron and has received more than 30,000 proposals.
MP Islington North says PMQs are too confrontational and that they will refrain from both "quick answers" and cog-trade, promising instead to focus on important issues such as poverty, inequality and the challenges faced by young people.
Mr Corbyn claims that Angela Eagle, the shadow trade secretary, will represent him at PMQ when he does not attend — such as when Mr Cameron travels abroad.
He also dropped the idea of letting other colleagues speak for him from time to time, saying he had discussed the matter with House Speaker John Bercow.
When Mr Cameron became leader in 2005, he said he wanted to move away from the "Punch and Judy" style of politics that was often associated with PMQ, but admitted years later that he had failed.
Since its first broadcast in 1990, PMQs have been seen as a key barometer of leaders' judgment, their leadership of the House and their stance among other MPs, although critics have argued that they have become a caricature and far-reaching reforms are needed.
