Opponents of the Prague apartment building are jubilant.
The controversial building was given a stopwatch.
The investor Praga Progetti e Investimenti considers the annulment of the decision to be illegal and will appeal against it.
Hundreds of people protested against the building, which is to be built in close proximity to the Convent of St. Agnes in the center of Prague, in front of the Prague 1 office, and a petition was also created.
In its decision, the City Hall stated that the Building Act had been violated because not all the requirements of the zoning decision had been met.
"The zoning decision in question does not contain some particulars, such as the type of land, distances from neighboring buildings, a sufficiently clear and comprehensible description of the shape of the building, the definition of the area affected by the impact of the building," the decision reads.
The Magistrate also considers it illegal that some of the documents for the decision were issued for the originally discussed documentation, which has been changed.
For example, the opinion of the environmental authorities.
Part of the building is to be built on the grounds of the National Gallery, but the investor does not have its valid consent.
The file material shows that the owner of the land only proved the consent to the project documentation for zoning proceedings, not the consent to the location of the building on his land, the Building Code Department writes.
According to Francesco Augusto Razetta from the investor company, the Building Code Department did not take into account the decision of the superior authority - the Ministry for Regional Development, according to which the deadline for initiating the review has already passed.
In any case, this is a scandalous procedure.
"We have been preparing this project for seventeen years, we comply with all the laws of the Czech Republic and we respect all the authorities and institutions concerned," Razetto said in a press release.
The project, which people call marshmelon because of the allegedly proposed color of the façade, evokes strong emotions in Prague.
In the past, hundreds of people gathered in the city center to protest against the construction.
Associations and residents of nearby houses are bothered by the fact that some permits were issued many years ago for a house that was supposed to look different.
They also criticize the unsuitability of the building for the historical center of Prague and the immediate vicinity of the Convent of St. Agnes.
The house was designed by architect Zdeněk Fránek, the project changed several times.
The original form of the project from 2008, which counted with a glass façade, was rejected by the Ministry of Culture on the basis of the opinion of the National Heritage Institute (NPÚ) and in 2010 the permission of Prague heritage officers was revoked.
However, the new project of Praga Progetti e Investimenti with face-shaped windows was approved by the National Heritage Institute and municipal heritage officers and a building permit was issued on this basis.
The author of the design rejects the criticisms of opponents, saying that he never counted on the façade in pink, which gave the project its nickname after the pink-and-white sweet.
