The December contribution of CZK 600 to pensioners is in jeopardy.
"It is justice of equal stomachs, it has nothing to do with human justice," said TOP 09 vice-chairman Miroslav Kalousek, who emphasized the principle of merit.
Zbyněk Stanjura, chairman of the ODS deputies, noted that the one-off contribution sounds good, but in the long run it would be better for it to be in the standard indexation, because it would be reflected in the coming years.
"We have room to find a mechanism to arrange this," Stanjura said.
He supported the original proposal of Minister Michaela Marksová (ČSSD), according to which next year it was to be indexed beyond the law.
Marks defended the subsidy by arguing that it would improve the social situation of pensioners, which she said is not rosy.
According to her, a higher valorization next year would mean a budgetary impact of 5.5 billion crowns, and ministers are discussing every hundred million.
Czech Prime Minister Bohuslav Sobotka (Czech Social Democratic Party - ČSSD) reminded the right that in the past it had reduced the pace of valorization.
Rapporteur Miroslav Opálka (KSČM) pointed out that the proposal does not address the reduction of real pensions in 2016 and later.
The right-wing's veto will significantly complicate and possibly make it impossible to pay in December, he said.
The chairman of the ČSSD deputies, Roman Sklenák, therefore proposed shortening the deadline for discussing the law in committee to ten or 20 days, which was also blocked by the right.
But the committee will have a month to do so instead of the usual two.
The bonus should cost the state a total of CZK 1.73 billion.
The money should come mainly from the budget of the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
Next year, pensions should increase by an average of about one hundred crowns.
According to the pension amendment, the contribution should be given to people who will be entitled to a pension or part of it in December.
It could also be obtained by those whose pension entitlement expired in December before it was paid.
However, they would have to apply for the surcharge in writing by the end of next year at the latest.
Pensions in the Czech Republic are indexed regularly as of January, by price growth and a third of real wage growth.
This year, the pension corresponds to 41.5 percent of the gross wage, next year it should be 40.5 percent.
According to the state final account, the state spent CZK 314.7 billion on old-age pensions last year, which was about five billion more year-on-year.
Expenditure on old-age pensions accounted for 26 percent of all budget expenditure and 46 percent of all expenditure required by law.
The average full old-age pension increased by CZK 104 to CZK 10,714 last year, according to data in the state final account.
The Czech Social Security Administration provided the payment of 2.4 million full old-age pensions and approximately 17,000 proportional pensions.
