Salt and pepper to taste, you can also flavor with ground chilli and soy sauce.
Finally, drizzle with a few drops of grape oil.
For an exceptional taste, you can then sprinkle the salad with finely chopped almonds.
Multiple sclerosis: it depends not only on medications, but also on the will of the patient to fight.
Multiple sclerosis is a complicated disease, and a person with this diagnosis needs the care of a number of specialists: neurologist, physiotherapist, occupational therapist, urologist, ophthalmologist, psychologist, psychiatrist and many other specialists.
However, it is not only about medical care, for example, women with multiple sclerosis also need consultations, if they decide to have a child, the care of these patients also includes social and legal counseling, recommendations for housing adjustment, etc.
Yet all this is not enough: the development of the disease can be fundamentally influenced by the patient himself.
The more he actively fights the disease, the longer he can work and does not have to fundamentally change his lifestyle.
As doctors point out, the passivity of the sick frees up space for the activity of the disease.
For example, it has been proven that regular exercise significantly delays the time when the patient needs a compensatory aid, such as a cane.
It is important that patients and their surroundings do not succumb to various myths, for example, that the disease automatically leads them to end up in a wheelchair.
That is why the Give Yourself a Chance (www.bezmytu.cz) page was created, which is supported by the ongoing media campaign Give Yourself a Chance.
The most important person in the care of a patient with multiple sclerosis is a neurologist.
In multiple sclerosis, the saying applies twice that the sooner the disease is treated, the more the doctor can influence something.
This is because we have drugs for multiple sclerosis in the inflammatory stage, when the process of neurodegeneration is not yet so strong.
The sooner we intervene, the greater the chance that we will be able to stop the disease and delay disability, explains Eva Medová from the Department of Neurology of the General University Hospital in Prague.
It is very important for people with multiple sclerosis rehabilitation care, which most often solves weakening of the lower limbs or balance disorders.
Patients are worked with according to their individual needs: to maintain fitness, improve walking, strengthen the pelvic floor, alleviate swallowing disorders or improve coordination.
"It is really individual, it depends on the specific problems of the patient," says Dr. Martina Kövári, head physician of the Department of Rehabilitation and Sports Medicine at the Motol University Hospital.
People with multiple sclerosis suffer from the same disease, but it manifests itself in a slightly different way for everyone.
Rehabilitation cannot stop the disease, but it can always alleviate its symptoms.
However, physical activity also strengthens the immune status of the body, which is desirable in the case of multiple sclerosis.
Another positive of regular exercise is the fact that patients check what they can do, and this strengthens their self-confidence.
"Exercise also releases endorphins and makes you feel good," says PhDr. Kamila Řasová from the Department of Rehabilitation Medicine at the University Hospital Královské Vinohrady.
By influencing the physical side, we act on the limbic system responsible for emotions.
We directly intervene in the psyche and immune processes and stabilize the disease, he adds.
"In the past, these patients were so-called sparing, today we know that they need a targeted load," says Prof. PaedDr. Pavel Kolář, Head of the Department of Rehabilitation and Sports Medicine at the Motol University Hospital.
The aim of physiotherapy is to allow a person to remain self-sufficient for as long as possible, including a job title.
Physiotherapists therefore cooperate with occupational therapists so that each person receives a compensation aid tailored to him.
Many patients also need the care of a psychologist or psychiatrist.
They are in a difficult life situation.
When a serious illness comes into your life, most people are shaken.
They experience shock, panic, fear.
They have to respond to a large load - loss of health.
With such a sore soul, we should go to someone, not try to bear everything on our own shoulders.
"I work with them so that they eventually come to the conclusion that even with a handicap it is possible to live a full life and that multiple sclerosis does not mean the end of life," says psychotherapist Renata Malinová - Schubertová from the Department of Neurology of the General University Hospital in Prague.
Without the Prague manufacturer Latecoere, airbuses would not fly.
Aerospace manufacturing is synonymous with precision and advanced technology.
New planes are full of titanium or light and strong composite materials that no one can produce and process.
Still, next to super-precise, computer-controlled machine tools, next to autoclaves for forming composites, you can come across something as ordinary as apricot stones.
In a drum that resembles a cotton candy pot, the edges of sheet metal parts that have just come out of the milling machine are tumbled in a pile of pits.
"So far, no one has come up with anything better," smiles Ivan Dubský, CEO of aircraft door manufacturer Latecoere Czech Republic.
On the premises in Prague's Letňany, the former Letov manufactures complete doors for the Airbus A320.
They are the only company in the world to supply doors for the Brazilian Embraer 170.
Through the doors, part of which is assembled in Prague, passengers also enter first and higher class on the upper decks of the world's largest airliner, the Airbus A380.
Doors full of composites for the new Boeing 787 Dreamliner are also assembled here.
Accuracy is the main motto here.
For example, the company has torque wrenches adjusted twice a year.
If the yellow sticker lacked a record of inspection, they would have something to explain to auditors from Airbus or Boeing, who regularly go to check whether the doors are manufactured according to the agreed rules.
However, advanced technology has not yet completely replaced the human senses.
There are 1500 rivets on one door to the A320.
These must be knocked by hand by the riveters.
It takes them two days.
Even by the sound of the hammer falling, they can tell if the rivet is already properly shaken.
The tolerance in which they move is minimal.
The rivet can rise above the surface of the aircraft from zero to 0.13 millimeters.
That's roughly twice the thickness of a human hair.
During the inspection, it is time to have a trained touch.
When the inspector runs his finger over a row of rivets, he knows if one is out of tolerance.
Only then does he pick up an accurate indicator.
Before 1989, Letov supported the L-39 military training aircraft program.
But in 1991, not one was produced.
The company had to quickly find new orders.
At that time, it teamed up with the European aircraft manufacturer Airbus.
It won the tender for an emergency door supplier for the A321.
The courtship with Boeing was not so happy.
"At that time, we were a small company that did not have enough money to invest and to guarantee Boeing long-term stable supplies," recalls Dubský.
The door to the American manufacturer would have remained slammed shut if Letov had not attracted the attention of the French group Latecoere at the Prague conference of the International Association of the Aviation Industry in 1999.
I talked about our cooperation with Airbus.
On the second day, negotiations with the French started, says Dubský.
A year later, Latecoere bought the Czech company and new orders came with the strong company.
In 2000, the installation of door parts for the A320 began.
Three years later, the upper deck doors for the A380 were added.
In 2006, the company built a new composites processing hall for deliveries for the Boeing Dreamliner.
Without Latecoere, we would not have been able to get to these large commissions ourselves.
Maybe we would do parts or small parts.
Partners want supply guarantees for twenty or thirty years, explains Dubský.
Last year, Czech Latecoere achieved a turnover of over CZK 2.9 billion and a profit after tax of CZK 147 million.
Exclusive position among suppliers of aircraft manufacturers does not come for free.
Latecoere has invested CZK 1.5 billion in Prague since 2000.
The company must have quality certificates, certification of 170 special production processes and qualification certificates for key employees.
Without them, the company would not produce any aircraft doors.
According to Dubský, obtaining certificates that production processes meet customer requirements and maintaining them in repeated inspections costs millions of crowns.
Production processes change every year.
They are more accurate and strict.
We have to train employees, retrofit the equipment and re-certify the whole process, adds Dubský.
Now the company is completing the preparation of a process for zinc and nickel plating, which will replace the existing cadmium harmful to human health.
Although they received the assignment from the manufacturer, they then had to adapt the technology for the equipment or chemicals they use in Prague.
People from Boeing will come, check the concept of the entire route.
Then we show them the production.
They will also check our laboratory.
They test one set of samples themselves in their laboratory and then compare the results with ours, explains Dubský about the way customers check them.
The Prague company is rewarded with long-term exclusive contracts.
Today, the production of embraers stands or falls with the Prague plant.
For the A320 produces half of the total volume of the doors.
Replacing the Czech Latecoere is either impossible or very difficult for a Brazilian or European manufacturer.
However, this does not mean that he can ask for any price at the door.
Part of the contract is the price curve.
It indicates how much one door will cost after ten, fifty, hundreds of pieces produced.
The price per piece keeps dropping towards a certain limit value.
We have to fit into this price formula.
If not, we will lose, says Dubský.
Half of the hall, where electrical cabinets for the Airbus A400 M military aircraft are assembled, is still empty.
However, it is a symbol of the future.
Behind the screen, a new semi-robotic line for riveting and door assembly for the innovated A320 Neo model is being built here.
Riveting becomes faster and more accurate.
"This is the trend that assembly in aviation is taking," adds Dubský.
Sales are assured for the future line.
Airbus reports that airlines have so far ordered 3278 units of the new A320.
Just a few metres away, a line will be built for the complete installation of doors for the upper deck of the A380.
It is a strategic decision of our parent company.
The aim is to reduce production times and costs.
Full assembly could begin within two years, says Dubský.
Before that, however, the company must pass qualification tests, for example, to install some electrical and electronic equipment in the doors of the largest Airbus.
The company also relies on further development of production from composite materials.
In addition to Boeing, it should also participate in the new Airbus A350 program, which will compete with the American Dreamliner.
"It is a huge credit for the company to be able to process composites in addition to metallic materials," says Dubský proudly.
However, Latecoere is reaching the edge of production capacities in the Czech Republic.
There is no other place in the Letov area, where it is located.
Before the entry of the French mother, the company had 180 employees.
Now it has 800, and in three years there could be a hundred more.
As long as Airbus and Boeing compete over how many hundreds of new planes airlines order each year, they don't have to worry about their jobs.
Although it has orders for several years ahead, the parent company of Prague's Latecoere faced the threat of bankruptcy.
The French group did not have enough money to repay the loans in September.
Eventually, Latecoere was able to negotiate with major creditors.
At the end of August, it exchanged part of the loans for shares.
Creditors acquired a 37.4 percent stake in the company by increasing their capital by 57.4 million euros.
The company's debt fell by two-thirds, or 180 million euros.
The second part of the financial recovery came at the beginning of September.
The company subscribed for new shares worth EUR 222.9 million among its existing shareholders.
In total, it raised share capital by EUR 280 million.
At the same time, the entire group benefits from the growing production of Airbus and Boeing, which account for 85 percent of sales.
It expects average order growth of four percent per year until 2017.
In the order book, it has orders worth 2.6 billion euros, which corresponds to four years of production.
French media claim that Latecoere can finally breathe again after years on drips.
The Czech plant in Letňany, Prague, is important for groups.
It contributes 16 percent to the group's revenues.
In terms of the number of employees, it is the largest foreign branch of the group.
MEPs supported a larger share of the state's share of coal charges.
The change in fees for mineral extraction should bring CZK 427 million more to the state treasury than in 2013.
According to the government, it should have a neutral impact on municipal budget revenues because the fee should be higher.
Last year, municipalities received about CZK 450 million from fees and the state budget CZK 150 million.
From brown coal mining, about 200 million crowns went to municipalities and 66 million crowns to the state.
The amendment also envisages an increase in the payment from mining areas with permitted mining to one thousand crowns per hectare per year.
The income from these payments is to continue to belong entirely to the municipalities.
Industry Minister Jan Mládek (ČSSD) told MPs that municipalities will receive CZK 14 million to 100 million annually instead of 14 million.
The amount of mining royalties will no longer be determined by law, but will be set by government regulation.
The remuneration is newly calculated as the product of the quantity of the extracted mineral and the rate for individual types of minerals.
According to the government, the reason for the change is, among other things, the possibility of a flexible response to the current economic situation.
ODS MP Marek Benda, however, warned that setting the fee by government decree may not be in accordance with the constitution.
According to Minister Mládek, however, this is not a tax because the state charges for a mineral that is state property.
Fees are paid only to municipalities whose territories are affected by mining.
In the case of underground coal mining, three-quarters of the money will go to municipalities and a quarter to the state.
The same ratio will be in the case of the extraction of radioactive rocks.
Part of the money collected by the state in mining royalties will be earmarked.
For example, 28 percent will have to go to repair damage after mining or to provide mining rescue services.
