"Sonogenetics" or control of brain cells using sound waves
This video shows how sound impulses affect the direction in which nematodes move.
Scientists have raised worms with genetically modified nervous systems that can control sound waves.
Tiny nematodes change direction when they are hit by sound impulses that are inaudible to the human ear.
The pulses work by switching the cells of genetically modified motor neurons, which are programmed to respond to these ultrasound waves.
Related: Scientists Can Read and Record Brain Activity Using Light
The researchers said these worms are a great example of a new methodology called sonogenetics, which uses ultrasound to activate brain, heart and muscle cells and activate outside the body.
Sreekanth Chalasani, a researcher at the Salk Institute in La Jolla, California, told the Guardian that the method could one day replace deep brain stimulation — an invasive procedure in which electrodes are inserted into a patient's brain to stimulate the brain. The method is used, for example, to treat the symptoms of Parkinson's disease.
Nematodes usually do not respond to ultrasound, but Chalasani found that reactions occur when they are placed in a liquid containing microscopic bubbles.
As he found out, the bubbles amplify ultrasonic waves, which then pass through the body of worms.
Amplified ultrasound waves act in TRP-4 ion channels, which are located in the membranes of some worm cells.
Thanks to sound waves, these channels open and activate the cells with which they are connected, according to a report in the journal Nature Communications.
In order to control the nematodes using ultrasonic waves, Chalasani genetically modified the worms so that some of their motor neurons contain TRP-4 ion channels.
When he applied ultrasound to the modified worms, the sound waves were amplified by microbubbles and transmitted to the worms, where they turned on the modified motor neurons.
The new method bears much resemblance to optogenetics, a pioneering tool that allows scientists to turn neurons on and off using light.
But Chalasani said sonogenetics could have many advantages over the technique.
Unlike light, which must be sent by an optical fiber to a desired location in the brain, ultrasonic waves can penetrate tissue without restriction and be sent directly to the brain.
"We believe that when we use gene therapy and therapeutic viruses, we can target human neurons and make them temporarily sensitive to ultrasound signals used in clinical treatment to treat neurological diseases," Chalasani said.
He added that the method would also find its application in the treatment of muscle cells and insulin-producing cells.
