And help others to take a breath too - ask questions and show interest.
It drives the conversation and helps you find people you like and people you wouldn't talk to even if your eyelashes were on fire and they were issuing fire extinguishers.
Give people space.
People's rooms often turn into drinking receptions, movie night locations and communal public places, but they are also rooms where people dress and adjust their underwear.
Related: Don't even think about going to college and being in a relationship
Introverts in college come up short.
Your room should be a refuge, yet many dorms turn into an out-of-room walking culture that is friendly, sociable, and contributes to lifelong friendships.
This can be hell for someone who needs to recharge.
No culture allows you to say, "I love you and I want our friendship to continue, but I need you to leave so I can get back to the energy I used to talk to you."
Try to recognize when a classmate is tired of socializing — and maybe write to him instead of knocking.
Speaking of knocking: knock.
One boy in my dorm used to be invited in if the door wasn't locked.
He saw a few things.
Make friends with baking.
Since you started going to university at the height of baking mania, knocking on someone else's door and performing with a slab baked cookies seems slightly less strange, less than, "Welcome to the neighborhood, I baked you something, now smile while I ask personal questions."
Offering homemade treats is a good way to make friends.
Your roommates will feel obligated to talk to you, and they may end up matching your face to a tasty surprise.
This, of course, is the subject of being a decent baker.
Poorly condensed pieces of flour, sugar, and lead are likely to make others pretend to sleep when you try to knock on their door.
Theft of food is a common crime in student dormitories.
Stealing a whole chicken is, of course, a crime, but is a drop of milk in your tea a theft?
Double check with the owner of the milk.
There is a chance that they will offer you milk even if they are raging inside.
If someone steals something from you, it's annoying and you have my sympathy - but try to deal with it a little more adult than my roommate who traded her milk for dishwashing detergent to punish the thief.
Now he's in prison.
You should not make sounds that disturb people from sleep or study.
It's not just about being a decent human being, but you're also a famous person in glass houses.
A girl from my hallway asked her neighbors if they could quiet down the drum and bass a bit because it was 3 at night and she had a test in the morning.
Their answer was to amplify the music.
When they finally fell silent at 5 a.m., she let them sleep peacefully for two hours and then turned on her own music, locked the door, and left for her three-hour test.
Wouldn't it be romantic if your future spouse went to the same dorms as you?
Conversely, wouldn't it be horribly embarrassing if you mistook roommates for your future spouse, slept together, broke up and had to see each other every day, and maybe she would also take control of your mutual friends?
Of course, you can't command your heart – but if your sexy roommate is definitely not your future spouse, try to talk to your weaknesses at least a little.
In the uplifting moment when you realize that someone has left the keys in their unlocked room, there is only a fine line between fun and bullying.
A good prank is funny, but easy to correct.
Teach them a valuable and fun lesson about keeping them secure by hiding something for them – never ruin someone's room with toothpaste and shampoo.
Lock their doors and put their keys in a water bottle to put in the freezer – but never stick their stuff on the ceiling more than twice.
Eva was looking forward to the twins despite uncertain future prospects.
Eva experienced hard times already during her pregnancy with the now seven-year-old Vítek.
His father broke up with her and she was alone in preparing and raising the child.
I coped with the situation quite quickly - I was very much looking forward to the baby and I was looking for positives in it.
I tried not to worry about the uncertainty and the fact that I would be alone with the child.
And I certainly had hope that we would not be alone for long, Eva recalls her first pregnancy today.
Already at that time, she met an older Vašek on the Internet chat, with whom they began to talk about their favorite films.
Vašek even drove Eva and Vítek home from the maternity hospital, but he did not rush into the role of stepfather.
"He then withdrew from the program for some time," Eva described in the documentary series Four in That 3.
The motif of the third season of the Czech Television series is the search for happiness on the second attempt.
She managed to take care of Vítek and the financial security of the family thanks to her part-time job and the great help of her mother and aunt.
Even the prospect of responsibility for someone else's child did not spoil Vašek's affection for Eva.
They finally got together around Vítek's second birthday and he now understands Vašek as his dad and also addresses him as such.
Although Vašek already has two adult daughters, he says he enjoys fatherhood at sixty and devotes more time to his children.
In addition to Vítek, they were joined by two-year-old Leontýnka and finally twins.
"Vasek came into our family somewhat naturally, maybe because my mother never talked much into my relationships," says a smiling Eva.
Not enough space?
At least we're close.
Twins Emma and Ela were born by caesarean section after Eva was diagnosed with cholestasis during pregnancy at the end of her pregnancy.
This is a disorder of the production and activity of bile acids, which are then in excessive amounts in the blood of a pregnant woman and are manifested mainly by itching.
The disease is dangerous for the unborn fetus, which is at risk of premature birth and death, in the mother after birth it usually disappears spontaneously.
To Eva's and Vašek's happiness, Emma and Ela were born healthy, even though they were only 36 weeks old.
Emička was placed in an incubator in the intermediate department, where Vašek's niece also works, who managed to take her over and accommodate her.
Elinka was bigger and immediately after the transfer from the ICU to the room I had her with me, says Eva, describing the challenging period after the birth.
She spent twenty days in the maternity hospital until the doctors agreed to release the babies, who had managed to reach the two-kilo mark in the meantime.
Waiting for the baby to be recruited in the maternity hospital did not make Eva happy.
"I was mad with nostalgia for my husband and children," the mother of four recalls the difficult moments in the postpartum department.
She and her husband also considered signing the reverse, among other things, because of the insensitive approach of one of the doctors.
However, this did not happen and the doctors released Eva and the twins into home care.
The stories of four pregnancies and births are broadcast by ČT1 on Tuesday evening at 9:45 p.m.
Quite a large family can be modest.
They live together in a small house near Prague, where Eva had to make do with an electric double hotplate and cramped conditions.
Although the house did not get bigger, Vasek made Eva happy by installing a gas stove to make the preparation of food for six people more comfortable.
When it's the best, we'll take turns taking a taxi.
Eva is convinced that children perceive mainly family comfort and a pleasant atmosphere, and not the size or shabbiness of the house.
So far, we have put together very nicely, better than we expected.
It's harder to hide the mess in a small space and we sometimes step over rolling babies, but at least we're all close, smiles Eva, who can find a positive side in every situation.
Vašek's work as a film lighting technician is no guarantee of regular income.
That's why he sometimes goes out into the streets of Prague as a taxi driver.
In his sixties, he says he can physically take care of the finances of his family and children, but how long will it be so?
"I realize that due to our age difference, one day I will be the one to feed this family," Eva admits frankly when asked about the future.
She would like to return to work, but she is even more attracted by the possibility of her own business.
With four children, I'm not exactly a target for employers.
And when the worst comes to worst, my husband and I can take turns taking a taxi, jokes the nice blonde.
Apple has suffered a yo-yo effect.
It's all the displays' fault.
A more powerful processor, a higher-resolution camera, a stronger chassis and a display that recognizes the power of touch are the strengths of the recently introduced ninth-generation iPhones.
The latter two also have a negative impact on the size and weight of the iPhone 6s and 6s Plus.
Apple's trend so far has been that each new generation of iPhone is lighter than the previous one.
The only exceptions were the third and fourth generations, whose weight has slightly increased compared to previous iPhones.
The two-gram weight difference to the detriment of the novelty was really negligible.
However, this is far from the case with the new iPhones.
Compared to last year's iPhone 6 and 6 Plus, the weight of the smaller model increased by 14 grams, and the larger one by 20 grams.
On the one hand, it is not surprising, last year's bending in Apple's pockets suffered considerably.
The chassis of the novelties is made of more durable aluminum alloy 7000, which is also reflected in the weight.
But it has a much bigger impact on the displays.
Apple has used 3D Touch technology for the novelties, thanks to which the displays recognize the power of touch.
To do this, it was necessary to provide the display with an additional layer of capacitive sensors.
The weight of the new iPhone's displays has more than doubled compared to previous generations.
For the smaller iPhone, from 12 grams to 29 grams, for the larger one, from 19 to 40 grams.
With iPhone 6s, the display is the heaviest component used.
The weight of only 143 grams is also achieved thanks to the slimming treatment, which touched most of the remaining components.
In the larger model, the heaviest element used is the battery, but its weight has not changed compared to its predecessor.
Even in this case, the largest increase is evident in the display.
The 5.5-inch iPhone 6s Plus weighs 192 grams.
How practical the new display technology will be will only become apparent during use.
The first users will be able to try it out on Friday, September 25, when the iPhone 6s and 6s Plus will go on sale in selected countries.
Have breakfast flakes been champions for tens of thousands of years?
In the Italian Grotta Paglicci, archaeologists have managed to find a find that opens up interesting possibilities.
They found traces of modern human settlement from different eras, including murals, tool remains, and so on and so forth.
But in layer 23A, which is mapped back about 30,000 years, scientists have discovered something that closely resembles the remains of a breakfast buffet.
Traces of oat grains were found on the spot, which apparently went through the process of producing today's so popular flakes.
Today, the grains are first soaked, then dried, stripped of the shell, the so-called plough, then scalded and distinguished flat.
In Paglicci cave, grains were discovered that were apparently heated or steamed, and then apparently crushed between two millstones - at least this is indicated by traces of use on two stones in the cave.
The researchers were unable to document in their publication for the journal PNAS that the cave had a complete snowflake making process, but the similarity is indeed striking.
We also have no evidence of how humans could have eaten the flakes, but the assumption that it was with some liquid and quite possibly warm is, of course, quite logical.
At the same time, it is a very interesting example of how intensively people used cereals long before the emergence of agriculture.
If the flake interpretation is correct, the oldest flakes preceded agriculture by about twenty thousand years.
