The symbol of the village came to life.
The wheel of the windmill above Chlum is spinning again after many years.
It can be seen from afar, because it is located on a fifteen-meter-high mast.
People from far and wide call it "fan on Chlum".
For the village with 150 inhabitants, it even became one of the elements of the municipal emblem, which the village received on the occasion of the meeting of natives in 2010.
"We applied for a coat of arms and of course we wanted to have a fan on the emblem, everyone in the area knows it," said Mayor Jiří Mašek.
The Chlum wind pump is a local technical monument.
It is also a bit of a memento of the present: it reminds us of the time when local people fought for quality drinking water.
The one in Chlum in the past centuries was a rarity.
It was not until 1910 that the Chlum representatives decided for a solution that was suitable until the mid-eighties.
In the village at the turn-off to Číchov they had dug a seven-meter deep well.
Three years later, the well was supplemented with a metal structure with a wind pump, which pumped water into a reservoir at the highest point of the village, near the local church.
"The construction was carried out by the company Antonín Kunc from Hranice na Moravě at a cost of 2,400 crowns," states a commemorative inscription on the ground floor fence of the mast structure.
After several repairs and falls of the wind wheel, the pump was used in 1971.
On May 7, 1973, a new chapter of the fight for water began to be written: on that day, a new water supply began to serve in Chlum.
The wind pump remained only a non-functional municipal symbol and a local rarity.
The landmark was put into operation at this year's meeting of natives.
It was not until 2008 that the Chlumský family decided to repair the wind wheel again and put it back into operation.
They had a replica of the original wheel made - reduced by half a meter in diameter.
The wheel was mounted on a mast, but it had to be brought down the same year.
The manufacturer of the replica did not choose the appropriate material and the bike could not withstand gusts of wind.
Then the Chlum landmark rested for several years dismantled under the roof.
Since June this year, however, the wheel on the high mast has been spinning again.
On the occasion of the meeting of natives, the municipality had the replica of the wheel modified and remounted it on the top of the iron tower.
But the wheel pumps service water from the well only into the overflow blind arm.
And over the summer we completely disconnected it, because there was little water in the well.
At least it was idle.
"In the autumn, we will disconnect the wind wheel shaft from the pump in the suction basket again," Mayor Mašek explained.
Chlum is not the only village in the Czech Republic where the wind wheel got into the municipal emblem, but it is the only village of this kind in the entire Highlands.
A similar element in the emblem is in honor of local technical monuments, for example, in Chvalkovice and Zelená Hora in the Vyškov region, in Kuželov in the Hodonín region, Partutovice in the Přerov region or in Police in the Vsetín region.
