I have to say that as a former journalist I am ashamed of my colleagues.
Ecology in practice.
When I once got up to a prefabricated apartment, I soon ceased to be the only inhabitant.
Silverfish moved into my Umakart toilet.
Silverfish, insects with imperfect transformation, i.e., not undergoing the transformation from a caterpillar to a beetle and the young looks like an adult individual, only it is tiny and gradually grows.
They were disgusting to me and I did not hesitate to kill them.
First manually and later chemically.
The socialist drugstore provided some kind of blue crystals for their disposal.
I think it was called Zyklon B.
Or something else?
However, it eliminated them successfully.
Later I dealt with the pharaohs in a similar way.
A box with a kind of juvenalizer, which the ants brought to the nest, and he then did not allow the queen to generate new offspring.
But I digress.
As time went on, insects became the object of my admiration, and I became more and more inclined to believe that they had the same right to life as we humans.
In addition, I have learned from life that interfering with the ecosystem does not lead to success and one pest can be replaced by another.
True, with fleas and bedbugs, I would probably not hesitate to aggravate my karma by killing them.
In our new home, my partner and I agreed that if the silverfish do not crawl behind our necks, let them eat the chips of fallen skin, some invisible eyelashes and so on.
Their peaceful existence was disturbed by a spider after some time.
He was a common kind of crook, who resided on the ceiling for a long time.
We thought it lived off occasional flies and mosquitoes, which only increased our comfort.
Because he spent several years with us, we found out that he feeds mainly on silverfish and that he probably kept their number at a tolerable number.
By intimate regular contact at each need performed, we found out that it was a female.
We have witnessed a romantic courtship with a partner about a third smaller, carefully strumming the threads of the web so that he is not eaten before he reaches the desired copulation.
It went on for about three days when they didn't move and didn't respond to our checks.
Under the toilet bowl, where the love games took place, we later found the remains of a dried male next to the female.
Then the spider did not move for weeks.
When we thought it was over, we were surprised by the number of small spiders hanging around it.
They soon disappeared.
Part of it was eaten by their mother, part of it was that they ran away.
Even the female disappeared somewhere after a week.
Whether she went elsewhere or died, we don't know, but after a month or two, she reappeared on the ceiling.
True, a little smaller, probably the daughter of the primeval inhabitant of the toilet.
For some time she watched our behavior cautiously from the ceiling, and by moving it under the toilet bowl, she evaluated our non-aggression as friendship.
The number of somewhat multiplied silverfish decreased again and the spider calmly watched its normal activities to provide food.
Our ecosystem hasn't changed all year.
Meanwhile, our daughter has reached an age where potty use has become a disgrace.
So far we have tolerated it, but the eternal pouring out of its contents has fed up.
We encouraged her more and more strongly to use the toilet.
However, the daughter found an excuse to maintain her habit in the spider, which she could see very well when wiping.
Our talk about seeing the spider did not take any luck in the house at all.
Crying and screaming, she forced her potty.
There was no choice.
There came a moment when the spider, in the interest of the daughter's developmental advancement, had to command.
It was up to me.
He was caught in a glass and banished over the balcony somewhere in the garden.
I said goodbye to him like a friend, but I still felt disgusting after living together for so long, as if I was throwing out a relative.
We assumed that silverfish would begin to appear more often and begin to multiply geometrically.
Surprisingly, for a week or two, none of them appeared.
I began to speculate about the cause.
I wondered if the spider had somehow grown them there, like the ants, that the environment of the toilet was not as favorable for their existence as we thought.
But then the first medium-sized pieces appeared, and they were teeming again.
I had to invent another theory as to the cause of their disappearance, and I discovered that their connection to the spider must have been due to the fact that if they did not see it, that it was hidden in some other place, and that they were in danger from anywhere.
Or, maybe they had some kind of telepathic connection with their predator, and his rapid disappearance caused some kind of alarm reaction in them.
All the more so because I have no illusions about their sight.
They showed some light shyness, but they didn't react to waving their hands or making quick movements.
My daughter already goes to the toilet regularly.
I think she's forgotten about the potty.
It remains only to attract some spider again.
I am already sending my wishes into the ether and I hope that they did not give up on me after the execution.
Otherwise, we would have to use Zyklon B.
