No one has explained to me how I should keep the accepted refugees in the country if they do not want to live in the Czech Republic.
Interior Minister Milan Chovanec (ČSSD) complained after a meeting with his European colleagues that other states are pushing the Czech Republic to accept quotas for the redistribution of refugees, but refuse any discussion.
He also notes that no one has yet explained to him how he should keep the allocated refugees in the Czech Republic, since they do not want to live here anyway.
"We did not receive an answer, and therefore we wanted the quotas to be removed from the final text," Chovanec told reporters.
Can you describe more specifically the position you came up with at the meeting of the European Union Interior and Foreign Ministers?
We do not agree with mandatory quotas as a system that simply cannot work.
We cannot speak of migrants as sacks of salt or flour.
They are living beings who have some visions, they are going somewhere, they have some relatives.
We wanted to hear from colleagues how we would be able to keep migrants on the territory of the Member States if they were redistributed.
We can't imagine it.
We did not receive an answer and therefore wanted quotas to be removed from the final text.
We have no problem with the other conclusions - functional hotspots, i.e. registration points, border protection, camps outside Europe, a trust fund for African countries and other things.
We have been talking about this for a year and we say that this is the way.
But to say that quotas will solve everything?
Not long ago we were dealing with forty thousand, now it's one hundred and twenty thousand.
When will it be five hundred thousand?
And how do we keep those people in that territory?
Ninety-eight percent of all people who cross us want to go to Germany.
Almost no one wants to come to us, we just don't know how to keep them here.
Other foreigners, Ukrainians, Vietnamese and others who take the Czech Republic as a destination country, get asylum in our country, have the ambition to come to us, but the interest of people from this migration wave, i.e. from Syria and other countries, is close to zero.
You mentioned that refugees don't really want to come to us, but we have already committed to accept fifteen hundred people.
Would it not be possible to accept more of them in this way?
We have committed to accept 1500 people, but with a condition.
We said: functional hotspots, border protection, military operation.
Even with those 1500, it is a matter of 1100 people coming with whom we will arrange the asylum procedure.
They will come to our detention facility and we will treat them the same as those we have captured.
It is a big question, and we will discuss this with Europe, whether we can detain people who will be registered in Italy and Greece or Hungary.
Because Europe's treatment is that if they have registration, they cannot be detained.
That is, they will come to our territory with registration, and if there is an agreement, which is not yet in place, it may happen that we will not even keep the 1100 on the territory of the Czech Republic and they will leave for Germany after their arrival.
If we can detain them for the duration of the asylum procedure, we will handle the asylum procedure with them.
According to European statistics, if they are citizens of Syria or Eritrea, almost 98 percent of them receive international protection.
Then they will be given documents that will allow them to travel around Europe.
And I think that these people will end up in the target countries again.
Then there are four hundred people who will be resettled.
This is the second project that is still under way, and we have only progressed there in discussing with the churches the possibility of helping them find employment, accommodation and so on.
But that's a very long run.
You said that at the ministerial meeting the other states were not willing to discuss with us.
But is it not the case that the Czech Republic is only rejecting quotas, but is not offering any solidarity step that would unblock the discussion?
And what exactly do you think this should be a step in solidarity?
If the Federal Republic of Germany issues an incentive that all migrants from Syria can join them, then the news will spread in a matter of hours throughout all camps in Europe, but also in Turkey and Jordan.
It encourages another wave of migration heading to Germany, because they simply do not want to come to us.
We think that the way is to protect the external borders - simply to discourage the migration waves, to help those in need, and to separate economic migrants.
To make it clear to them that they have no chance.
Last year alone, fifty thousand Kosovars came to Germany.
From a safe Kosovo, where we pay for all the saturation of this state, including the police, the courts, the prosecutor's offices.
If we managed to separate them and not accept them, or accept them only according to the needs of the economies, then fifty percent of what the social systems spend on them today in vain could go to refugees.
Compared to the first day when Germany introduced controls, the number of detainees in the Czech Republic jumped.
Now it's eighty, the first day it was twelve.
How far should it go to tighten border controls even further?
We were afraid of being caught in the order of hundreds of people.
These are the numbers we can handle.
We still have several hundred vacancies in brick-and-mortar detention facilities.
Of course, all the people we detain will be returned to Austria within seven days.
We do this as standard.
The Austrians are the only ones who are taking these people away from us, with Hungary it is difficult and the Greeks - this is a completely useless story.
So where is the tipping point?
Would it have to be a thousand a day?
I think it would have to be several hundred a day.
Two hundred, three hundred people a day, two, three consecutive days will exhaust our capacities so much that crisis plans will begin.
Then I agreed with the Prime Minister that he would immediately convene an extraordinary government.
He is very interested in the whole thing, we are in contact several times a day on the phone.
If this situation arises, the government can de facto sit immediately and by one resolution it would decide to strengthen the police with the army, let's say the customs administration, or the prison service.
The extreme option is the state of emergency that Hungary has now declared in some places?
I don't think it can get that far.
Remember that our position is different, we are a national state within Europe, we have a Schengen border only and only at the airport.
I don't know what would have to happen for this to happen in the Czech Republic, I don't want to spread alarm.
All the information we have, whether from Moldova, Serbia, Hungary, suggests that the Hungarians will try to divert the migration flow to Croatia and Slovenia, which would then mean a direct route to Austria.
The Czech Republic would be affected very marginally, almost not at all.
