FedEx Earnings Mixed, Cut Fiscal Outlook for 2016
FedEx reported disappointing results for the quarter and a huge cut in its full-year profit forecast due to low freight demand and higher ground costs.
The company also said it plans to hire about 55,000 seasonal workers over the holidays.
During this period last year, FedEx announced that it would hire 50,000 seasonal workers for the holidays.
The company's shares fell about 2.5 percent in pre-market trading 45 minutes before Wednesday's open.
FedEx says it expects earnings of between $10.40 and $10.90 for the fiscal year ending next May, down 20 cents from its previous forecast.
Analysts had expected $10.84, according to a survey conducted by FactSet.
The lowered outlook comes despite an average 4.9 percent interest rate hike in January. 4, and higher surcharges for the land transport of heavy or large packages, starting in November.
The company said it still expects earnings growth over the previous year due to cost reductions, higher revenue and growth in online commerce.
Chairman and CEO Fred Smith said the company "delivered solid performance despite weaker-than-expected economic conditions, particularly in manufacturing and global trade."
The vacation hiring plans were announced a day after rival UPS said it planned to hire 90,000 to 95,000 extra workers, about the same as they hired last year.
In a quarter that ended in August. 31, FedEx raised $692 million, up 6 percent from last year.
Earnings-per-share were $2.42, less than $2.44 per share, as predicted by 12 analysts surveyed by Zacks Investment Research.
Revenue increased 5 percent to $12.3 billion.
Six analysts surveyed by Zacks had expected $12.23 billion.
FedEx has been hit by a decline in priority international shipping in recent years, causing revenue in its Express Unit to stagnate.
But the boom in online shopping boosted the results of the FedEx ground unit.
In the most recent quarter, ground revenue grew 29 percent, but operating profit was essentially the same due to higher prices for larger packages and custom insurance.
The express unit saw higher revenue due to higher base rates, while profit declined in the freight trade due to higher labor prices.
In premarket trading about an hour before the open, FedEx shares fell $3.85, or 2.5 percent, to $150.15.
They ended Tuesday down 11 percent for the year and 17 percent below the record set on June 11.
In their most anticipated meeting in years, Federal Reserve lawmakers will spend two days seated at Honduras' 27-foot mahogany table this week deciding whether it's time to raise a key interest rate after nearly a decade.
Towering over them at one end of the central bank ornament, the two-story meeting room will be a mural of the United States.
The map is a reminder that Fed Chairwoman Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues are supposed to put the nation's economic interests above all else.
The central bank has a dual charge from Congress: maximize American employment and keep prices stable.
But since the Great Recession, Fed officials have acknowledged that there is an unwritten third term: financial stability.
And this third term could be an X-factor too close to a predictable decision to be announced Thursday on whether the U.S. economy is poised to be triggered in a near-zero short-term interest rate shutdown since late 2008.
While most of the data point to solid economic growth, the recent turbulence in global financial markets could scare the already cautious Fed into adding to volatility by raising its reference federal funds rate – by nothing more than a quarter of a percentage point.
"Obviously, the labor market and inflation will be the most important thing to watch in the first place," said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
"But I think they were just looking for an excuse not to increase the rate, the increased uncertainty surrounding the global market already gives them ample justification to wait any longer," she said.
There is no consensus on what the Fed will do, which in itself is causing nervousness in financial markets.
About half of economists recently surveyed by Blomberg predicted a rate hike this week.
However, financial markets expect the Fed to delay the matter, with a key indicator of only about a 30% chance of an increase.
That would point to a stock market decline if the Fed raises rates only if policymakers soften the slump by promising that no further hike is in sight.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average jumped 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599.85.
The rally was triggered by expectations that Fed policymakers would hold rates quietly this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
"It would be a surprise if the Fed raised rates now," he said.
If Fed politicians did that, "they would have to go to the extreme in their policy statement and hold the hands of financial markets so they wouldn't panic."
Other experts argued that raising rates would reassure financial markets because it would remove uncertainty about how the Fed would proceed.
Just a month ago, the Fed appeared to be on track to raise rates by 0.25 percentage points this month, the first small step in a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would confirm the strength of the U.S. economic recovery.
Yellen said she expects rate hikes this year through the spring and early summer, despite complaints from liberals that more economic progress is needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, the labour market has seen solid growth this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% the previous month, the lowest in more than seven years and close to what the Fed considers full employment.
Wage gains showed signs of lifting.
And while inflation remains below the central bank's annual 2% target, Fed policymakers say the main reason was the temporary effect of significantly lower oil prices.
The economy "can cope with higher rates and needs them, given the tightness of the labor market," said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But financial markets around the world began to convulse late last month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones' industrial average fell as much as 16% below its record high in May as investors feared that China's slowing economy would drag down global growth.
The market has bounced back somewhat this month, and the Dow is now losing only nearly 10% from its May high.
For Fed policymakers, the turbulent market situation gives them a comprehensive calculation of when to start raising the interest rate.
"In the absence of what has happened in the financial markets and the reports of weakness in the Chinese economy over the past couple of weeks, there would be a tightening at this meeting," said Stephen D. Oliner, a senior research fellow at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former Fed official.
Now he predicts that they will wait at least a month to gain better control over the consequences.
"There's a lot of uncertainty about what impact this will have on the U.S. economy, and they have almost no data to rely on for the latest developments in China," Oliner said.
The health of the global economy is not one of the Fed's main concerns, so technically it should not be included in their decision-making.
But in reality, the Fed has become the monetary authority of the world.
The central bank's influence in recent years has been enormous.
The mere suggestion by then-Chairman Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed might "narrow" their monetary expansion in the market triggered convulsions around the world.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, Fed officials can be expected to monitor developments elsewhere, but also consult with other central bankers and experts to better read the state of the global economy.
Their decision-making process is "more art than science," said Zachary Karabell, head of global wealth-management strategy at Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, Va., noted this month that "the Fed has a history of exaggerated movements in financial markets that seem inconsistent with economic fundamentals."
Lacker, a voting policymaker at the Federal Open Market Committee who pushed for rate hikes, cited the 1998-99 decision as an example.
The financial crisis in Asia led the Fed to cut its benchmark rate by 0.75 percentage points over three meetings "Despite limited identifiable effects on U.S. growth," Lacker said.
A year later, Fed officials reversed the cuts.
The Fed should prioritize financial stability concerns only during a major recession like the 2008 market meltdown, said Adam Posen S., a former member of the Bank of England's rate-setting committee.
The latest turmoil is not even close to that level, he said.
"You certainly don't want to be in a situation of fear of a rate hike because the markets are upset," said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still has a dual mandate and does not mention financial stability, and until that changes, I don't think they should come out on top.
