Speeds on motorways will remain the same.
Acceleration to 150 km/h was rejected by the Chamber of Deputies.
On selected motorway sections, it will not be possible to increase the speed limit up to 150 km/h under favourable conditions.
On Tuesday, the Chamber of Deputies made the decision when it acceded to an amendment by the Senate that rejected the speed increase.
The amendment to the Road Act will now head to the President.
President Miloš Zeman said at the end of April that he would veto the law allowing one hundred and fifty kilometers of speed.
Transport Minister Dan Ťok (for ANO) was also against the increase, according to which the Czech motorway network is not yet built for such speed.
Ťok supported the Senate version of the bill in front of deputies on Tuesday.
In accordance with the original government proposal, the approved amendment will now allow an increase in speed from 90 to 110 kilometres per hour on selected first-class roads, especially four-lane roads.
The Chamber of Deputies first extended this option to motorways, which could be driven at speeds of up to 150 km/h in selected sections, but the Senate rejected it.
Members have now acceded to his proposal.
With the consent of the Minister of Transport, the senators also exempted from the amendment the right of the traffic police to have the last word in the regulation of local roads that are taken care of by municipalities.
The Senate version, which was approved by the Chamber of Deputies, also assumes that sewers, water mains or public lighting cables can be laid longitudinally under the road surface.
Municipalities would thus save on the purchase of land.
Municipalities should also not be obliged to look after road vegetation along local roads, regardless of the owner of the land in question.
The amendment should also help improve road protection and make it easier for municipalities to handle towed vehicles that the owners do not report to.
Newly, municipalities could sell towed vehicles that their owners do not register within a six-month period after notification of towing.
Municipalities will be able to exclude transit freight transport through their territory on second- and third-class roads under the threat of fines for forwarding companies.
The amendment also abolishes the possibility to introduce electronic vignettes instead of the current paper ones, which will be used after 1 January next year.
According to the government, this will save money on the introduction of an electronic system.
