Hungarian police reportedly briefly detained an AP cameraman at the border with Serbia and forced him to delete footage of a police dog allegedly knocking a fugitive to the ground.
But the Hungarian government disputes this accusation.
The alleged incident happened Saturday night when AP cameraman Luca Muzi filmed migrants crossing the border with Serbia through a cornfield near the Hungarian town of Röszke.
Police officers intervened against the refugees, and one of them attacked a Syrian man with a dog with a basket on his nose.
The dog threw the man who shouted "Please, please, I'm a refugee," the man said.
The fact that the man was filming everything was noticed by one of the policemen and did not allow him to leave.
The journalist was then no longer allowed to call his superiors or colleagues on the spot.
Officers took Muzi to a dark spot near a refugee registration center and asked him to show them what he had recorded.
He was then ordered to delete the recording.
The man thus lost the result of two days' work in Serbia and Hungary.
He says he felt in danger because there were dogs nearby.
The Associated Press sent a letter of protest to Hungarian government spokesman Zoltán Kovács.
In it, she called the officers' behavior unacceptable and said journalists should be able to cover events without risking physical violence and not having to worry about the government destroying legally obtained material.
Citing a police report, Kovács disputed Muzi's account of the events.
He said the officers just wanted the journalist to show them if they were in any of the footage, which he said they had the right to do.
