For mildly obese diabetics, weight loss surgery could be helpful
The benefits of weight loss surgery for mildly obese people with type 2 diabetes may last at least five years, according to a new study.
However, it's too early to say whether mildly obese people with type 2 diabetes live longer after weight loss surgery than those who receive non-surgical treatment.
"Mortality data takes a long time to show," says Dr. Robin Blackstone, an expert in weight loss surgery who wrote an op-ed for a new study of JAMA surgery.
Operations for weight loss, bariatric surgery use various methods to reduce the size of the stomach.
Reducing hunger and limiting the human body to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgeries have proven effective for treating type 2 diabetes, but most research has been done on people with morbid obesity with a body mass index (BMI) of 25 or higher.
BMI, which measures the relationship of weight relative to height, is considered normal between 18.5 and 24.9.
A BMI of 25 or higher indicates that a person is overweight, and people above 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For their new studies, researchers from the Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan used data collected from a study collected since 2007, which looks at two types of bariatric surgery — gastric bypass and gastrectomy — in type 3 diabetes treatments for people who were mildly obese.
The average BMI among those who underwent surgery dropped from 31 to 24.5 by the end of their fifth year, according to the study.
Meanwhile, the BMI of those who did not receive surgical treatment for diabetes remained roughly the same at 29.
Among patients with surgery, diabetes was resolved completely in 36 percent and partially in 28 cases.
In comparison, in the drug-treated group, diabetes was resolved completely in only 1 percent and partially only in about 2 percent of patients.
Controls for blood pressure, trigycerides, and "bad" LDL cholesterol were also shown to be "generally better in the surgical group," the authors found.
The researchers also monitored the patient's hemoglobin A1c levels in the blood, which reflects the body's ongoing blood sugar levels.
Hemoglobin A1c is best kept below 7 percent, the researchers report.
After surgery, the average hemoglobin A1c dropped from about 9 percent to about 6 percent.
In the drug-treated group, however, this figure remained at about 8 percent.
But this better "glycemic control" — which translates into better hemoglobin A1c levels — did not reduce mortality at five years, according to lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The research team also compared average results with two types of surgeries.
After the fifth year, the bypass group lost more weight compared to the gastrectomy group (18.7 vs. 14.2 kg), achieved larger declines in BMI (7.4 vs. 5.1) and hemoglobin A1c (3.1 percent vs. 2.1 percent), and were more likely to remission diabetes (46.9 percent vs. 16.7 percent).
While the new study doesn't show an improvement in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study of stronger people in Sweden where they found that surgery leads to longer life, says Blackstone of the University of Arizona College or Medicine-Phoenix.
According to a Swedish study, obese people who underwent bariatric surgery had about a 29 percent greater chance of survival over the next 15 years, compared to a group that tried more conventional methods.
While the new study didn't show an improvement in survival among patients after surgery, Blackstone said it's a reassuring outcome for people with a BMI below 35 who are interested in these procedures.
"This is where this work is critical because it states that surgery is safer in the lower BMI group," without increasing the risk of death or kidney disease, he says.
Blackstone also argues that people and their doctors should start taking weight really seriously after a patient's BMI drops between 27 and 30.
"I think we've waited too long to let people know the seriousness of the situation," he says.
