How the refugee crisis has shattered the Schengen area.
The emergency flare fired by Germany has far not cemented the European crew, but is already forcing the ship to change course, French daily Le Figaro reports.
The European Union decided on Monday to tackle the refugee problem first: it will systematically sort migrants and asylum seekers as soon as they set foot on the Old Continent — particularly in Greece — rather than arguing over the future distribution of refugees by quota based on quantities that are increasingly distant from reality.
Six days after European Commission President Jean-Claude Juncker asked 25 of the 28 EU countries to redistribute 160,000 refugees, member states' interior ministers changed the priority.
Rather than worrying about the final destination of refugees, it is first necessary to filter those who arrive today and resolve the fate of those who are already moving within the Schengen area.
"Effective management of the EU's external borders is essential to manage migration," stressed a text discussed by ministers in Brussels on Monday.
After the crisis of the common currency, the EU finds itself in jeopardy in its next major integration project.
Germany may be surprised, but it is not losing its resolve and is increasing the pressure.
It is reinstating border controls, particularly with Austria, but without blocking the flow of those seeking asylum in the country.
The Central Power thus makes it clear that without it, no free movement in Europe is possible.
The fact that Austria and Slovakia joined the measure on Monday already served as proof.
Poland, the Netherlands, Belgium and even France are also considering this, albeit with varying intensity.
Hungary did this a long time ago.
Such exceptional and temporary measures shall be permissible under Schengen rules.
That it is a domino effect, but he also sees blind.
