French Interior Minister Bernard Cazeneuve and his German colleague Thomas de Maizière discussed this intensively during a private conversation with their three colleagues from Greece, Italy and Hungary.
This idea is by no means new, but it is being implemented with difficulty.
In Italy, according to unofficial statistics, two-thirds of newly arrived migrants have already been registered and identified with fingerprinting.
Budapest rejects the introduction of any entry point on its territory because it fears more than others that it will be left with camps in which refugees would accumulate at its expense.
Greece remains the real black hole.
More than 200,000 people have landed on its islands near the Turkish coast this year, twice as many as recently arrived in Italy.
Most are genuine asylum seekers who came straight from Syria after passing through overcrowded camps in Lebanon, Turkey and Jordan.
It's a huge gaping hole.
Athens, which is still in financial turmoil and waiting for a new government, has folded its hands.
This is the starting point for the Balkan route and a source of now shared concerns for German Chancellor Angela Merkel and Hungarian Prime Minister Viktor Orbán.
The Juncker Commission promises to introduce checkpoints as soon as possible, but has given no number or date.
"The challenges facing Greece extend to the whole of Europe," EU interior ministers agreed on Monday to mobilize on that front.
It is therefore a question of deploying intervention teams from the European border control agency Frontex in the country.
The EU wants to help Greece expand its capacity to receive asylum seekers and strengthen surveillance of the islands.
"Adequate financial resources will be needed," warns the text submitted to ministers for approval.
In terms of law, Athens will continue to have the final say.
The question of the creation of real European border guards has not been officially raised, but Europe is getting close.
In any case, the new emergency situation of the twenty-eight has put on the back burner the issue of binding quotas and 160,000 refugees, which was raised by the Juncker Commission and the European Parliament at the beginning of the year and strongly supported by Angela Merkel and French President François Hollande.
Hungary, Slovakia, the Czech Republic and Poland still do not want to hear about it.
They see this as an attack on their sovereignty.
The number, but not the obligation, was retained on Monday in the text approved by a majority of the twenty-eight.
