In the event of the bankruptcy of the travel agency, insurance companies should pay the clients' claims in full.
Insurance companies should cover the claims of clients in the event of bankruptcy of a travel agency in full.
This was decided on Wednesday by the Chamber of Deputies when it approved a modified amendment to the Act on Business Conditions in Tourism.
Travel agencies will be able to replace bankruptcy insurance with a bank guarantee, according to the draft heading to the Senate for consideration.
Insurance companies do not agree with the obligation to pay clients' claims even above the agreed limit.
The Ministry of Regional Development insists on the regulation, arguing consumer protection.
Insurance companies have already threatened to stop insuring tour operators against bankruptcy if the amendment goes into effect.
However, the proposal is also criticised by travel agencies.
Without insurance, they will either have to quit or go abroad.
Minister for Regional Development Karla Šlechtová (for ANO) pointed out that cases where insurance companies have not paid full compensation are not Eurocompatible.
She drew attention to this year's decision of the Constitutional Court, which confirmed that the client is entitled to a full refund regardless of the insurance limit.
Insurance companies will receive enough information about the management of travel agencies and will be able to determine the correct limit, Šlechtová emphasized.
"We appreciate the effort to increase consumer protection, but it must have such a limit to be feasible," said TOP 09 vice-chairman Miroslav Kalousek.
According to him, the bank guarantee will not work, because no one will give it unlimited.
"Travel agencies will have to close down or move abroad," Kalousek warned.
Tomio Okamura (SPD), a member of the Presidium of the Association of Czech Travel Agencies and Travel Agencies, disagreed with Kalousek's concerns based on a survey among member travel agencies.
"Stop showing us the lobbying of insurance companies," he said.
Okamura does not consider the statements of the insurance companies to be relevant, and there is no official written statement to this effect.
However, they are finding out whether travel agencies will pay a deductible, which according to Okamura is not a problem.
Jana Fischerová (ODS), who referred to the opinion of the rival Association of Travel Agencies of the Czech Republic, and her party colleague Petr Bendl, who spoke about lubricating the stairs for Czech travel agencies, also warned against the provision.
According to Fischerová, travel agencies will not be able to arrange insurance.
"Consumer protection works," Fischer said.
Her motion to delete the disputed passage was not approved by the House.
Vojtěch Filip (KSČM) did not come forward with a proposal to return the draft to the committee due to an alleged conflict with the Civil Code.
Filip drew attention to travel agencies, which, according to him, can endanger consumers.
Due to the Constitutional Court's verdict, the rapporteur for the bill, Martina Berdychová (ANO), withdrew her proposal, which would limit the liability of insurance companies in cases where they could not know that the insurance benefit would not cover the entire risk.
The amendment will not include the originally proposed minimum limit of four million crowns of insurance for travel agencies that offer air tours and the million limit for agencies selling, for example, bus tours.
The threshold will remain at 30 percent of planned sales of tours.
However, the indemnity limit will have to be such that it covers all customer claims in the event of the travel agency's bankruptcy.
Even after amendments, the standard stipulates that travel agencies will have to indicate which travel agency organises the package when selling tours.
Travel agents will have to provide insurance companies with, inter alia, economic and number of travel data before concluding a contract.
The approved amendment of the Public Administration Committee also envisages further regular information of insurance companies.
Travel agents will have to provide them on a monthly basis with data on the number of passengers and package holidays sold, the total price of the tours sold and the amount of advances and revenues for tours and vouchers.
If the Ministry of Regional Development finds that the travel agency has not fulfilled any of its legal obligations towards the insurance company, it will call on it to remedy the situation or prohibit it from concluding new contracts if the breach of duty could endanger the interests of customers.
The amendment should also newly regulate the financing of the Mountain Rescue Service.
The Ministry of Regional Development will determine the amount of the subsidy to the Mountain Rescue Service on the basis of its application, which will always be submitted by the end of April for the following year.
The application will include a report on the use of state money in the past year, a financial plan of expenditure and an outlook for the next two years.
According to the association, however, the proposer of the bill did not think through the situation of what would happen if the insurance company terminated the travel agency's contract.
It will not be allowed to organize tours and clients who bought the package before the cancellation of the insurance will lose it, according to the association.
In this case, the travel agency will suffer a significant loss and may even go bankrupt, even though its management was in good shape.
One of the ways in which travel agencies can cope with such a situation will be to sue the state for compensation.
Another option will be to go abroad and take advantage of much softer conditions abroad, and then we will only act as agencies on our market, said Jan Papež, vice-chairman of the association.
According to him, the draft amendment also contains the institute of a bank guarantee, but it is so ill-considered that it cannot be implemented in practice at all, because a bank guarantee cannot be for an unlimited amount.
Moreover, according to the association, changing the existing practice is de facto unnecessary.
In the next two years, the entire law will have to be revised again in view of the new EU directive.
A total of 942 active insured travel agencies currently operate on the Czech market.
This year, only three travel agencies have ceased their activities.
Domestic travel agencies sell tours worth about twenty billion CZK a year.
