Xi calls for opening up economy to wider world
It is necessary to open the economy to the wider world to boost growth, President Xi Jinping told the group tasked with Tuesday's governance reform.
"China should engage in attracting foreign investment and expertise and improve open policies," he said of the 16th session of the central leader of the group to deepen overall reform.
Promoting opening up to emerging reforms will give new impetus and vitality, as well as provide new scope for economic growth, Xi said.
The Steering Group adopted a number of directives, including a negative list of regulatory market access, a relaxation of border control policy, support for state-owned enterprises (SOEs) to absorb private capital, and the reorganization of the resident registration system.
The statement states that a negative list will be drawn up in which sectors and enterprises that are outside the investment limits will be identified.
This system will be gradually tested and improved through trial programmes.
The move is significant because it will give the market a greater role in allocating resources, ensuring a legal business environment and making the market more open, the statement said.
The government will also relax controls on the powers it delegates to firms, and make sure that the firms themselves decide how to run their business.
The statement also states that China will allow border areas to discover new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms to promote regional growth.
In an effort to open up a state-controlled industry, more areas will be opened to private investment.
"The government will not change its policy towards foreign investment and will protect the legitimate interests of foreign-funded companies and provide them with better services," the statement said.
In addition, it will be easier for foreigners to apply for a permanent residence permit or "green card" by optimizing requirements and simplifying the application process.
Ensuring the rights of lawyers to practice and develop professional judges and prosecutors was also discussed at the meeting.
Premier Li Keqiang and leaders Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli also attended the meeting, according to a statement issued after the meeting.
New inpatient wards may be established in the Karlovy Vary Region.
According to Deputy Governor of the Karlovy Vary Region Jakub Pánik (ČSSD), the current capacity of inpatient departments of two regional hospitals and two private hospitals in the region is sufficient and partial adjustments should be made on the basis of an agreement between the departments of individual hospitals.
However, there are also possibilities for expanding care in the region.
For example, one-day surgery centers could be established in the departments of surgical departments, where surgical procedures that do not require hospitalization longer than 24 hours would be performed according to the set concept.
It is not yet clear in which specific hospitals there should be one-day surgery clinics.
At the dermatology department of the Karlovy Vary hospital, a laser center could be established with the possibility of using laser technology for skin diseases.
The concept also recommended the establishment of an apallic center that would care for patients with brain impairment who are in a vegetative state.
Such a centre should be established centrally and should be an integral part of the anaesthesiology and resuscitation department.
There is also the possibility of concentrating such a facility in the Ostrov hospital, where similar care already exists.
Another bed capacity that seems to be insufficient in the Karlovy Vary Region are aftercare beds, especially the beds of the Long-Term Patient Hospitals (LDN), whose capacity in Nejdek is insufficient and, above all, should be closely linked to acute care beds.
Part of this facility should function as rehabilitation beds and part as classic LDN beds, the concept recommends.
As he points out, aftercare beds are mainly lacking in the Karlovy Vary hospital.
There could be used abandoned buildings after centralization.
Last but not least, in the Karlovy Vary Region there is a lack of social and medical beds with a focus on the treatment of Alzheimer's disease.
There is a shortage of these beds throughout the country, so it could serve for other regions as a so-called Alzheimer center.
According to the recommendations, hospitals should also prepare for the introduction of so-called follow-up beds, for which European subsidies will be released.
"These are beds that will follow the fields of supespecialized care and will form a space for the transfer of patients after the procedure, for example, after cardiac surgery, neurosurgical, transplantation or other interventions," describes the regional concept of inpatient care.
New services could also be offered in the field of psychiatric care.
